[2026-03-09T23:45:12Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CT9FoPv8jKPRSypQybG5Xy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19→file is a parse error.\n    20→\n    21→## Concepts\n    22→\n    23→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    29→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    30→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    31→\n    32→## Step Types\n    33→\n    34→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35→\n    36→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39→\n    40→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42→\n    43→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45→\n    46→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47→parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## DSL Syntax\n    50→\n    51→```\n    52→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53→  step code {\n    54→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55→    container {\n    56→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58→    }\n    59→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  step check {\n    63→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64→    results = [pass, fail]\n    65→  }\n    66→\n    67→  step review {\n    68→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69→    input = step.code.output\n    70→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n    74→  code:success -> check\n    75→  code:fail -> abort\n    76→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77→\n    78→  check:pass -> review\n    79→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80→\n    81→  review:approved -> done\n    82→  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83→}\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→## Key Properties\n    87→\n    88→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89→field makes it a script step.\n    90→\n    91→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93→\n    94→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97→\n    98→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100→\n   101→## Wire Output Mappings\n   102→\n   103→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   104→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   105→\n   106→```\n   107→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→The general form:\n   111→\n   112→```\n   113→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   117→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   118→\n   119→| Expression | Meaning |\n   120→|---|---|\n   121→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   122→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   123→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   124→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   125→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   126→\n   127→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   128→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   129→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   130→\n   131→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   132→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   133→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   134→\n   135→## Host Workflow Example\n   136→\n   137→```\n   138→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   139→workflow \"main\" {\n   140→  step ready-tasks {\n   141→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n   142→    results = [success, fail]\n   143→  }\n   144→\n   145→  step prepare-prompt {\n   146→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   147→    results = [success, fail]\n   148→  }\n   149→\n   150→  step develop {\n   151→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   152→    results       = [success, fail]\n   153→  }\n   154→\n   155→  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n   156→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n   157→    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n   158→    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n   159→  ]\n   160→  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n   161→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n   162→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n   163→  ]\n   164→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   165→  develop:success        -> done\n   166→  develop:fail           -> done\n   167→}\n   168→```\n   169→\n   170→The `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\n   171→them as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\n   172→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n   173→\n   174→## Execution Model\n   175→\n   176→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   177→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   178→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   179→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   180→\n   181→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   182→steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   183→standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   184→etc.) are injected into each step.\n   185→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b72ad31e-d71e-41fa-bc07-3bb633eb718f","uuid":"fe8f4858-e46a-4b62-bae5-17877a51713b","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Runs on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  step ready-tasks {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh 1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  ready-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n  ]\n  ready-tasks:fail       -> abort\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop [\n    CLOCHE_TASK_ID = output.task_id\n  ]\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `ready-tasks` step outputs JSON; wire output mappings extract fields and inject\nthem as environment variables into `prepare-prompt`. The `workflow_name` step\ndispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes.\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\nsteps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\nstandard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\netc.) are injected into each step.\n","numLines":185,"startLine":1,"totalLines":185}}}
